<questestinterop>
  <item ident="_u5_m1_digtutor21a" title="question_1">
    <presentation>
      <material>
        <mattext texttype="text/plain">Using the same sample mean (115) and population standard deviation (15), estimate &#181; with a 97% confidence interval.</mattext></material>
      <response_lid rcardinality="Single" ident="LID_01">
        <render_choice>
          <response_label ident="Res4">
            <material>
              <mattext texttype="text/plain">(113.5, 116.5)</mattext></material></response_label>
          <response_label ident="Res3">
            <material>
              <mattext texttype="text/plain">(112.2, 117.8)</mattext></material></response_label>
          <response_label ident="Res2">
            <material>
              <mattext texttype="text/plain">(111.7, 118.3)</mattext></material></response_label>
          <response_label ident="Res1">
            <material>
              <mattext texttype="text/plain">(111.5, 118.5)</mattext></material></response_label></render_choice></response_lid></presentation>
    <resprocessing>
      <outcomes>
        <decvar varname="SCORE" vartype="integer"/></outcomes>
      <respcondition>
        <conditionvar>
          <varequal respident="LID_01">Res4</varequal></conditionvar>
        <setvar varname="SCORE">0</setvar>
        <displayfeedback feedbacktype="Response" linkrefid="FeedBack0"/></respcondition>
      <respcondition>
        <conditionvar>
          <varequal respident="LID_01">Res3</varequal></conditionvar>
        <setvar varname="SCORE">0</setvar>
        <displayfeedback feedbacktype="Response" linkrefid="FeedBack1"/></respcondition>
      <respcondition>
        <conditionvar>
          <varequal respident="LID_01">Res2</varequal></conditionvar>
        <setvar varname="SCORE">10</setvar>
        <displayfeedback feedbacktype="Response" linkrefid="FeedBack2"/></respcondition>
      <respcondition>
        <conditionvar>
          <varequal respident="LID_01">Res1</varequal></conditionvar>
        <setvar varname="SCORE">0</setvar>
        <displayfeedback feedbacktype="Response" linkrefid="FeedBack3"/></respcondition></resprocessing>
    <itemfeedback ident="FeedBack0">
      <material>
        <mattext texttype="text/plain">Incorrect. It appears that you used 0.97 standard deviations to find your interval. This is the area in the center of the interval, not the number of standard deviations. Please try again.</mattext></material></itemfeedback>
    <itemfeedback ident="FeedBack1">
      <material>
        <mattext texttype="text/plain">Incorrect. It appears that you used 1.88 standard deviations to find your interval. This comes from a tail area of 1 − 0.97 = .03. Recall that this area must be divided in half. Please try again.</mattext></material></itemfeedback>
    <itemfeedback ident="FeedBack2">
      <material>
        <mattext texttype="text/plain">Correct. To have 97% confidence there is (1 − 0.97)/2 in each tail. Looking up this area (0.015) we find that the number of standard deviations (z-score) is 2.17. Thus, the confidence interval is: (&lt;a href="javascript:loadImage('../../../webcontent/flash/_u5_m1_digtutor21a.jpg')"&gt;&lt;font color="#CC6666"&gt;&lt;u&gt;click here to view formula&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;)</mattext></material></itemfeedback>
    <itemfeedback ident="FeedBack3">
      <material>
        <mattext texttype="text/plain">Incorrect. A 97% confidence interval would not have limits halfway between those for 95% and 99%, since the distribution is not uniform, but normal. A 97% confidence interval has an area of 0.97 in the center of a normal distribution or 0.485 on each side of the mean. To find the number of standard deviations we must look up the tail area. Please try again.</mattext></material></itemfeedback></item></questestinterop>
